Every control and every application has to belong to a Business Unit — that's how the platform knows who to ask for evidence, who's accountable, and where audit trails should land. In the past, this was institutional knowledge — someone in the team just knew who owned what, or it lived in a spreadsheet that often went stale.
The platform replaces that with two simple setups, done once.
The first is for business processes. There are only a handful, and they rarely change. The Risk Manager picks each process from a list and points it to its Business Unit. Take process zero zero two — it's mapped to Application Engineering. Process zero zero four — mapped to Platform Engineering. One process, one Business Unit. Easy to maintain. Easy to audit.
The second is for applications. LeanIX already knows where each application sits in the organization — it stores a path like Bank slash Wealth slash PlatformOps. The Risk Manager defines short patterns that the platform watches for. The pattern "Wealth slash PlatformOps" tells the platform: this application belongs to the Wealth Business Unit. Set the patterns once; the platform applies them to every application, every cycle.
And every row has a status. Mapped means the platform resolved it cleanly. Unresolved — like MEA02 here — means the platform couldn't find a match; the Risk Manager either adds an explicit mapping, or marks the row Ignored if it intentionally has no owner. Some processes are Horizontal — they cross multiple Business Units. The platform recognizes that pattern too. Blank Business Units aren't errors; they're work items, surfaced by the platform so nothing falls through the cracks
